The History of Johnnie Walker Whiskey.

The available records for whiskey history in Scotland are dated back to the 15th Century. However, the art of making whiskey had been earlier introduced in Europe around the 12th Century. Initially, whiskey was a solution used for medical purposes such as to cure pox. The making of these medicines was solely done by the monarchs. Gradually in the reign of King Henry VIII, the monasteries were dissolved and this birthed the making of the medicinal spirit “uisge” aka “whiskey” in the Scot households. Over time people realized that the whiskeys could be used for refreshment in the right amounts and thus a growing need to perfect the making. However, the whiskeys made had no consistent taste and thus tasted different in every serving. ‘John Walker’ a young grocery owner in Kilmarnock at that time was really set and focused to create a consistent taste and flavor for his customers. He started blending whiskies together until he created a whiskey he was happy to put his name to. This was the birth of the iconic Johnnie Walker Blended Scotch whiskey brand.

How Johnnie Walker is made.

Now, Johnnie Walker has various brands and this is to say that there are many different ways in which the brands are made.

In general, whiskey making has over the years moved from cottage industries to precision processes that now involve a lot of technology and automation.

The final flavor and character of any brand of whiskey are dependent on the making process. That is, from the type of grain used, the yeast involved, the shape of the stills, the casks make, and of course, the time allowed for maturation of the whiskey.

In Scotland, there have been two dominant whiskey varieties.

  • The bold smoky West Coast malts.
  • The gentle Highland whiskeys.

The whiskeys all go through these whiskey-making processes.

(1) Malting.

(2) Mashing.

(3) Fermentation.

(4) Distillation.

(5) Maturation.

(6) Bottling.
